{{Infobox Korean name |img= |caption= |hangul=혜원풍속도 or 혜원풍속도첩 |hanja=[[wikt:蕙|蕙]][[wikt:園|園]][[wikt:風|風]][[wikt:俗|俗]][[wikt:圖|圖]] or [[wikt:蕙|蕙]][[wikt:園|園]][[wikt:風|風]][[wikt:俗|俗]][[wikt:圖|圖]][[wikt:帖|帖]] |rr=Hyewon pungsokdo or Hyewon pungsokdocheop |mr=Hyewŏn p'ungsokto or Hyewŏn p'ungsoktoch'ŏp |}}
'''Hyewon pungsokdo''' is an album of the [[genre paintings]] (''pungsokhwa'' or ''pungsokdo'') drawn by the Korean painter [[Shin Yunbok]] during the late [[Joseon dynasty]]. It was named after Shin's [[pen name]], '''Hyewon''', and comprises 30 paintings in total.
In 1930, [[Jeon Hyeopil]] (전형필:全鎣弼), later the founder of the [[Gansong Art Museum]], purchased it from an antique dealer in [[Osaka]], [[Japan]] and newly mounted the album. [[Oh Sechang]] (오세창), who was a journalist and pro-independence activist, wrote the subtitles and postface for the album. ''Hyewon pungsokdo'' is designated as the 135th [[National treasures of South Korea|National Treasure of South Korea]] and is held in the collection of the [[Gansong Art Museum]] located in [[Seongbuk-gu]], [[Seoul]], South Korea.<!--Is it on display there or kept in a vault?-->
