Japan's medieval period (the [[Kamakura period|Kamakura]], [[Nanbokuchō period|Nanbokuchō]] and [[Muromachi period|Muromachi]] periods) was a transitional period for the nation's literature. [[Kyoto]] ceased being the sole literary centre as important writers and readerships appeared throughout the country, and a wider variety of genres and literary forms developed accordingly, such as the ''[[gunki monogatari]]'' and ''[[otogi-zōshi]]'' prose narratives, and ''[[renga]]'' linked verse.

== Overview ==
[[History of Japan#Medieval Japan|Japan's medieval period]] lasted roughly 400 years from [[Minamoto no Yoritomo]]'s establishment of the [[Kamakura shogunate]] and being named [[shōgun]] in [[Kenkyū|Kenkyū 3]] (1192) to [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]]'s establishment of the [[Edo shogunate]] in [[Keichō|Keichō 8]] (1603) following the [[Battle of Sekigahara]] in Keichō 5 (1600) that began the [[Edo period]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} This period, based on the centres of political power, is normally divided into the [[Kamakura period|Kamakura]], [[Nanbokuchō period|Nanbokuchō (or Yoshino)]], [[Muromachi period|Muromachi]] and [[Azuchi–Momoyama period|Azuchi–Momoyama]] periods, and is also referred to simply as the [[Kamakura-Muromachi period]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} The start date of this period has also been taken as being around 1156 (the [[Hōgen rebellion]]) or 1221 (the [[Jōkyū rebellion]]), with the Azuchi–Momoyama period also sometimes being taken as part of the [[History of Japan#Early modern Japan|early modern period]], with the medieval period ending at [[Oda Nobunaga]]'s entry to [[Kyoto|the capital]] in [[Eiroku|Eiroku 11]] (1568) or the end of the Ashikaga regime in [[Tenshō (Momoyama period)|Tenshō 1]] (1573).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

The period is characterized by war, beginning with the [[Genpei War]] and ending with the Battle of Sekigahara, with other conflicts such as the Jōkyū rebellion, the war between the [[Northern Court|northern]] and [[Southern Court|southern court]]s and the [[Ōnin War]] (1467–1477), culminating in the entire country erupting in war during the [[Sengoku period]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} The social order was disrupted as a result of these conflicts, with changes to society in general and, naturally, shifts in literary styles and tastes.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} The philosophy of [[impermanence]] (無常 ''mujō'') became pervasive, with many seeking salvation, both physical and spiritual, in religion, specifically [[Japanese Buddhism|Buddhism]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

=== Aesthetic ideals ===
The basic ideal that informed aesthetic tastes in this period is known as ''[[yūgen]]'', along with other concepts such as ''[[yūshin]]'' (有心) and ''[[yōen]]'' (妖艶).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} These ideals shunned realism, representing a spirit of ''[[l'art pour l'art]]'' and aiming to plunge the reader into an "ideal" world, and were in accord with the ideals of Buddhist monastic seclusion (出家遁世 ''shukke-tonsei'').{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} What exactly constituted ''yūgen'' differed throughout its history, and the various literary genres it influenced include ''[[waka (poetry)|waka]]'', ''[[renga]]'' and ''[[noh]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} Later developments include ''[[en (literature)|en]]'' (艶), ''[[hie (literature)|hie]]'' (ひえ) and ''[[wabi-sabi|sabi]]'', connecting to the [[Edo literature|literature of Japan's early modern period]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

Translator and literary historian [[Donald Keene]] discusses both ''yūgen'' and ''hie'' (which he translated "chill") as concepts shared by the quintessentially medieval art forms of ''renga'' and ''noh''.{{sfnm|1a1=Keene|1y=1999|1pp=999–1000}} He describes ''sabi'' as having been "used to suggest the unobtrusive, unassertive beauty that was the ideal of Japanese poets, especially during the turbulent decades of the Japanese middle ages",{{sfnm|1a1=Keene|1y=1999|1loc=689, note 73}} and states that it first came to prominence around the time of the ''[[Shin-kokin Wakashū]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Keene|1y=1999|1loc=661}}

There was, however, a concurrent trend toward a form of realism in medieval developments on the concept of ''[[okashi]]'' (をかし).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} Authors began to attempt to reflect reality in order satirize social conditions, or for simple enjoyment.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

=== Authors and readership ===
Medieval Japanese literature is most often associated with members of the [[samurai|warrior class]], religious figures and hermits (隠者 ''inja''), but the [[kuge|nobility]] maintained a degree of their former prestige and occupied an important position in literary circles.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} This was especially true in the early middle ages (i.e., the Kamakura period), when court literature still carried the high pedigree of earlier eras, while monks, recluses and warriors took an increasingly prominent role in later centuries.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} Furthermore, at the very end of the medieval period (i.e., the Azuchi–Momoyama period), urban (''[[chōnin]]'') literature began to appear.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} This led {{illm|Teiji Ichiko|ja|市古貞次}}, in his article on medieval literature for the ''[[Nihon Koten Bungaku Daijiten]]'', to conclude that the medieval period was the time when the literature of the nobility became a truly national [[Japanese literature]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

Developments in the performing arts allowed for large groups of people to appreciate literature on a broader level than before.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} As the social classes that had previously supported the arts fell away, new groups stepped in as both creators and audiences for literary works.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} These conditions encouraged the growth of a literature that was more visual and auditory than the [[Heian literature|literature of Japanese classical period]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} This is true of performing arts like ''nō'' and [[buyō|traditional dance]], but also includes such genres as the ''[[emakimono]]'', which combined words and images, and ''[[e-toki]]'', which conveyed tales and Buddhist parables via images.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

The centre of culture continued to be the capital in Kyoto, but other areas such as [[Ise, Mie|Ise]] and [[Kamakura]] became increasingly prominent as literary centres.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

== Literature of the early medieval period ==
=== Historical background of the early medieval period ===
The early medieval period covers the time between the establishment of the Kamakura shogunate and the shogunate's collapse roughly 140 years later in [[Genkō (second)|Genkō 3]] (1333).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} With the shogunate, who were of warrior stock, controlling the affairs of state in eastern Japan, the aristocracy of the [[Imperial Court in Kyoto|Heian court]] continued to perform limited court functions and attempted to preserve the aristocratic literary traditions of the past.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} The first two or three decades, which are also known as the ''Shin-kokin'' period, saw a surge in interest in ''waka'' composition and attempts to revive the traditions of the past.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} However, with the failure of the Jōkyū rebellion and [[Emperor Go-Toba]]'s exile to [[Oki Island]], the court lost almost all power, and the nobility became increasingly nostalgic, with the aristocratic literature of the later Kamakura period reflecting this.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

As the warrior class was in its ascendancy, their cultural and philosophical traditions began to influence not only political but also literary developments, and while literature had been previously the exclusive domain of the court this period saw a growth in the literature of other levels of society.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} Narrative works such as ''[[The Tale of the Heike]]'' are an example of this new literature.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

Buddhism was also in its heyday during this period, with new sects such as [[Jōdo-shū]], [[Nichiren-shū]] and [[Zen Buddhism|Zen-shū]] being established, and both old and new sects fervently spreading their influence among the populace throughout the country.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} In addition to [[Buddhist literature]] such as ''[[hōgo]]'', the monks of this period were especially active in all manner of literary pursuits.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} Those who became hermits upon entering Buddhism produced a new kind of essay, the ''[[zuihitsu]]'', as well as fine examples of ''[[setsuwa]]'' literature.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} Such literature is known as [[hermit literature]] (隠者文学 ''inja-bungaku'' or 草庵文学 ''sōan-bungaku'', "thatched-hut literature").{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

Overall, the literature of this period showed a strong tendency to combine the new with the old, mixing the culture of aristocrats, warriors and Buddhist monks.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

=== Early medieval ''waka'' ===
The ''waka'' genre saw an unprecedented level of exuberance at the beginning of the Kamakura period, with Emperor Go-Toba reopening the [[Waka-dokoro]] in [[Kennin|Kennin 1]] (1201).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} Notable, and prolific, poets at the highest levels of the aristocracy included [[Fujiwara no Yoshitsune]] and his uncle, the [[Tendai]] abbot [[Jien]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} At both the [[Heian imperial palace|palace]] and the homes of various aristocrats, poetry gatherings (''[[uta-kai]]'') and competitions (''[[uta-awase]]'') such as the famous ''{{illm|Roppyaku-ban Uta-awase|ja|六百番歌合}}'' and ''{{illm|Sengohyaku-ban Uta-awase|ja|千五百番歌合}}'' were held, with numerous great poets coming to the fore.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} On Go-Toba's command, [[Fujiwara no Teika]], [[Fujiwara no Ietaka]] and others compiled a new ''[[chokusenshū]]'' (imperial ''waka'' anthology), the ''Shin-kokin Wakashū'', which was seen as a continuation of the grand ''waka'' tradition begun three hundred years earlier with the ''[[Kokin Wakashū]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} Ichiko calls this the final flowering of the aristocratic literature, noting its high literary value with its basis in the literary ideals of ''yūgen'' and ''yūshin'', its emphasis on suggestiveness, and its exquisite delicacy.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}}

The foundations for this style of poetry were laid by Teika and his father [[Fujiwara no Shunzei|Shunzei]], not just in their poetry but in their highly regarded works of poetic theory (''[[karon (poetry)|karon]]'' and ''[[kagaku-sho]]'').{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} These include Shunzei's ''{{illm|Korai Fūtei-shō|ja|古来風体抄}}'' (also valuable as an exploration of the history of ''waka'') and Teika's ''{{illm|Maigetsu-shō|ja|毎月抄}}'' and ''Kindai Shūka'' (近代秀歌).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=258}} Such works had a tremendous influence on later ''waka'' poets, and their philosophy of ''[[fūtei]]'' (風体) has had value for Japanese aesthetics and art generally.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1pp=258–259}} Other works of the ''karon'' genre include those that are noted for their recording of various anecdotes about ''waka'' poets, including [[Kamo no Chōmei]]'s ''{{illm|Mumyō-shō|ja|無名抄}}''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

This flourishing was characteristic of the first three or four decades of the Kamakura period, but following the Jōkyū rebellion and the exile of Go-Toba, the great patron of ''waka'', the genre went into decline.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Teika's son, [[Fujiwara no Tameie]], championed simplicity in ''waka'' composition, writing the ''karon'' work ''[[Eiga no Ittei]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} In the generation following Tameie, the ''waka'' world became divided between schools represented by the three great houses founded by Tameie's sons: [[Nijō family|Nijō]], [[Kyōgoku family|Kyōgoku]] and [[Reizei family|Reizei]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} The conservative [[Nijō school]], founded by Tameie's eldest son, was the most powerful, and with the different schools supporting different political factions (namely the {{illm|Daikakuji-tō|ja|大覚寺統}} and the {{illm|Jimyōin-tō|ja|持明院統}}), there was less emphasis on poetic innovation than on in-fighting, and the genre stagnated.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

The compilation of imperial anthologies, though, actually became more frequent than before, with a ninth anthology, the ''[[Shin-chokusen Wakashū]]'', and continuing on regularly over the following century until the sixteenth, the ''[[Shoku-goshūi Wakashū]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Of these eight, the only one that was compiled by a member of the Kyōgoku school was the ''[[Gyokuyō Wakashū]]'', compiled by [[Kyōgoku Tamekane]], and this is considered the second best of the Kamakura anthologies after the ''Shin-kokin Wakashū''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Every other collection was compiled by a Nijō poet, and Ichiko notes that there is little of value in them.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} However, in eastern Japan the third shōgun, [[Minamoto no Sanetomo]], a student of Teika's, showed great poetic skill in his [[kashū (poetry)|personal anthology]], the ''{{illm|Kinkai Wakashū|ja|金槐和歌集}}'', which shows the influence of the much earlier poetry of the ''[[Man'yōshū]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

Overall, while poetic composition at court floundered during the Kamakura period, the courtiers continued the act of collecting and categorizing the poems of earlier eras, with such compilations as the ''{{illm|Fuboku Waka-shō|ja|夫木和歌抄}}'' and the ''[[Mandai Wakashū]]'' (万代和歌集) epitomizing this nostalgic tendency.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

=== ''Monogatari'' ===
Works of courtly fiction continued to be produced by the aristocracy from the Heian period into the Kamakura period, with the early Kamakura work ''[[Mumyō-zōshi]]'', written by a devout fan of ''[[monogatari]]'', particularly ''[[The Tale of Genji]]'', emphasizing literary criticism and discussing various ''monogatari'', as well as ''waka'' anthologies and other works by the court ladies.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} The work praises ''Genji'' and then goes on to discuss various works of courtly fiction in roughly chronological order, and is not only the sole work of such literary criticism to survive from this period but is also valuable for detailing the history of the genre.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

The ''[[Fūyō Wakashū]]'' is a slightly later work that collects the ''waka'' poetry that was included in courtly fiction up to around [[Bun'ei|Bun'ei 8]] (1271).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} This work was compiled on the order of [[Emperor Kameyama]]'s mother [[Ōmiya-in]] (the daughter of [[Saionji Saneuji]]), and shows not only the high place courtly fiction had attained in the tastes of the aristocracy by this time, but the reflective/critical bent with which the genre had come to be addressed in its final years.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Well over a hundred ''monogatari'' appear to have been in circulation at this time, but almost all are lost.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Fewer than twenty survive, and of the surviving works, several such as ''[[Sumiyoshi Monogatari]]'', ''[[Matsuranomiya Monogatari]]'' and ''[[Iwashimizu Monogatari]]'' (石清水物語) have unusual contents.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Other extant ''monogatari'' of this period include''{{illm|Iwade Shinobu|ja|いはでしのぶ}}'', ''{{illm|Wagami ni Tadoru Himegimi|ja|わが身にたどる姫君}}'', ''{{illm|Koke no Koromo|ja|苔の衣}}'' and ''[[Ama no Karumo]]'' (海人の刈藻).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

Late Kamakura works of courtly fiction include ''{{illm|Koiji Yukashiki Taishō|ja|恋路ゆかしき大将}}'', ''{{illm|Sayo-goromo|ja|小夜衣}}'' and ''{{illm|Hyōbu-kyō Monogatari|ja|兵部卿物語}}'', and these works in particular show a very strong influence from earlier works, in particular ''The Tale of Genji'', in terms of structure and language.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Long works of courtly fiction at this time were almost all ''{{illm|giko monogatari|ja|擬古物語}}'', or works imitative of past ''monogatari'', and production of them largely ceased during the Nanbokuchō period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

=== Early medieval ''rekishi monogatari'' and historical works ===
Works that continued the tradition of Heian ''[[rekishi monogatari]]'' such as ''[[Ōkagami]]'' and ''[[Ima Kagami]]'' were written during this period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} ''[[Mizu Kagami]]'', for example, recounts the history of Japan between the reigns of [[Emperor Jinmu]] and [[Emperor Ninmyō]], based on historical works such as the ''[[Fusō Ryakuki]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}
''[[Akitsushima Monogatari]]'' (秋津島物語) attempted to recount events before Jinmu, in the [[age of the gods]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

More serious historical works composed during this period include the ''[[Gukanshō]]'', which describes the period between Emperor Jinmu and [[Emperor Juntoku]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} It also attempted to describe the reasons for historical events and the lessons to be learned from them, and unlike the historical romances being produced at court that reflected nostalgically on the past, the ''Gukanshō'' used history as a way to criticize present society and provide guidance for the future.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} It is also noteworthy for its simple, direct language, which was a new innovation of this period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

=== Early medieval ''gunki monogatari'' ===
The historical and court romances were a continuation of the works of the Heian period, but a new genre that built upon the foundations laid by these emerged in the Kamakura period: the ''[[gunki monogatari]]'', which is also known as simply ''gunki'', or ''senki monogatari''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} The immediate predecessors of these works were ''[[kanbun]]'' chronicles composed in the Heian era such as the ''{{illm|Shōmonki|ja|将門記}}'' and ''{{illm|Mutsu Waki|ja|陸奥話記}}'', as well as warrior tales included in the ''[[Konjaku Monogatari-shū]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

The ''gunki monogatari'' emerged in the early medieval era as a form of popular entertainment, with the most important early works being the ''[[Hōgen Monogatari]]'', the ''[[Heiji Monogatari]]'', and ''The Tale of the Heike''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} These three recounted, in order, the three major conflicts that led to the rise of the warrior class at the end of the Heian period. They were composed in ''[[wakan konkō-bun]]'', a form of literary Japanese that combined the ''[[yamato-kotoba]]'' of the court romances with Chinese elements, and described fierce battles in the style of [[epic poetry]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} They portrayed strong characters proactively and forcefully, in a manner that Ichiko notes was appropriate for the age of the warrior class's ascendancy.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} The ''Heike'' in particular was widely recited by ''[[biwa-hōshi]]'', travelling monks, usually blind, who recited the tale to the accompaniment of the ''[[biwa]]'', and this was a very popular form of entertainment throughout the country all through the middle ages.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

The authors of these works are largely unknown, but they were frequently adapted to meet the tastes of their audiences, with court literati, Buddhist hermits, and artists of the lower classes all likely having a hand in their formation.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} There are, consequently, a very large number of variant texts.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} In addition to the largely unprecedented manner in which these works were formed, they led to the rise of ''{{illm|heikyoku|ja|平曲}}'' style of musical accompaniment.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

Following these three, the ''{{illm|Jōkyū-ki|ja|承久記}}'', which recounted the events of the Jōkyū rebellion, was also compiled.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Together, the four are known as the ''Shibu Gassen-jō'' (四部合戦状).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} The ''[[Soga Monogatari]]'', which composed toward the end of this period, placed its focus on heroic figures, and laid the foundations for the ''gunki monogatari'' of the Muromachi period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

Some ''gunki monogatari'' in this period took the form of picture scrolls.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

=== Early medieval ''setsuwa'' literature ===
Similarly to new the innovations in the collection and categorization of ''waka'' poetry in the Kamakura period, the period saw an upswing in the compilation and editing of ''[[setsuwa]]'', or short tales and parables.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} This included aristocratic collections such as the ''[[Kokon Chomonjū]]'', the ''[[Kojidan]]'' and the ''{{illm|Ima Monogatari|ja|今物語}}'', as well as the ''[[Uji Shūi Monogatari]]'', which also incorporates stories of commoners.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Other works targeted at members of the newly ascendant warrior class had a stronger emphasis on disciplined learning and [[Confucianism]], as exemplified in the ''{{illm|Jikkinshō|ja|十訓抄}}''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

Buddhist ''setsuwa'' works were meant to provide resources for sermons, and these included the ''{{illm|Hōbutsu-shū|ja|宝物集}}'' of {{illm|Taira no Yasuyori|ja|平康頼}} and Kamo no Chōmei's ''{{illm|Hosshin-shū|ja|発心集}}'', the ''{{illm|Senjū-shō|ja|撰集抄}}'' and ''[[Shiju Hyakuin Nenshū]]'' (私聚百因縁集).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} Of particular note are the works of monk and compiler [[Mujū Dōgyō]], such as ''[[Shaseki-shū]]'' and ''[[Zōdan-shū]]'' (雑談集), which mix fascinating anecdotes of everyday individuals in with Buddhist sermons.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

These ''setsuwa'' collections, like those of earlier eras, compile tales of Buddhist miracles and the nobility, but works like the ''{{illm|Kara Monogatari|ja|唐物語}}'' also incorporate tales and anecdotes from [[China]], and some include tales of commoners, showing a change in tastes in this new era.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

Some works describe the origins of [[Buddhist temple]]s and [[Shinto shrine]]s and collect tales of miracles.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1pp=259–260}} Such works include the ''[[Kasuga Gongen Genki]]'' and the ''{{illm|Kokawa-dera Engi|ja|粉河寺縁起絵巻}}'', both of which are ''emakimono'' that combine words and images.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}} These are a development of the earlier ''[[engi (literature)|engi]]'' that were written in ''kanbun'', but Ichiko notes that they should also be considered a form of ''setsuwa''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=259}}

=== Early medieval diaries, travel literature and essays ===
Ladies at court continued to write [[nikki bungaku|diaries]] as they had during the Heian period, with important examples including ''{{illm|Nakatsukasa no Naishi Nikki|ja|中務内侍日記}}'' and ''{{illm|Ben no Naishi Nikki|ja|弁内侍日記}}''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} Of particular interest are diaries written by women who became ''{{illm|nyoin|ja|女院}}'' (court ladies) during the [[Taira clan|Taira]] ascendancy such as ''{{illm|Kenshun-mon'in Chūnagon Nikki|ja|建春門院中納言日記}}'' and ''{{illm|Kenrei-mon'in Ukyō no Daibu Shū|ja|建礼門院右京大夫集}}'', which provide a glimpse of life behind the scenes at the palace.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}
The latter in particular, written by [[Kenrei-mon'in Ukyō no Daibu]] had come to court to serve [[Kenrei-mon'in]], is focused primarily on poetry that conveys her sadness and lamentation, following the downfall of the Taira clan in warfare, which shows a character quite different from the ladies' diaries of the Heian period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} ''[[Towazu-gatari]]'', a work by [[Go-Fukakusain no Nijō]], combines reflections on her time serving at court with a travelogue.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} It provides a bare-faced look at the inner thoughts and desires of its author, which is rare for a work written by a woman of this period, causing Ichiko to compare it to the [[I novel]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

Literary diaries written in Japanese by men, such as [[Asukai Masaari]]'s ''[[Haru no Miyamaji]]'' (はるのみやまぢ, also known as 飛鳥井雅有日記 ''Asukai Masaari Nikki'') began to appear.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} The tradition continued of ''[[kanbun-nikki]]'' (diaries in [[classical Chinese]]) used to record the day-to-day lives of the nobility also continued, of which Teika's ''[[Meigetsuki]]'' is the best-known example.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

Because of the biregional nature of government in this period, with the court in Kyoto and the shogunate in Kamakura, works describing the journey along the [[Tōkaidō (road)|Tōkaidō]] between Kyoto and Kamakura, such as ''{{illm|Kaidōki|ja|海道記}}'', ''{{illm|Tōkan Kikō|ja|東関紀行}}'', and the nun [[Abutsu]]'s ''{{illm|Izayoi Nikki|ja|六十夜日記}}'' began to appear ''en masse''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} ''Kaidōki'' and ''Tōkan Kikō'' were written by highly educated men in ''wakan konkō-bun''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

''[[Takakura-in Itsukushima Gokōki]]'' (高倉院厳島御幸記) is one important example of the growing subgenre of travelogues describing pilgrimages to shrines and temples.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} ''[[Ryūben Hōin Saijōki]]'' (隆弁法印西上記) recounts the [[Tsurugaoka Hachimangū]] ''[[bettō]]'' {{illm|Ryūben|ja|隆弁}}'s journey to [[Onjō-ji]] and the time he spent there.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} It was likely composed by one of Ryūben's travelling companions, and is noteworthy partly for its unusual gaps in describing the journey, and for its frank portrayal of the perversity<!-- "狂態や稚児との愛欲" --> of the monks.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

Works discussing the rejection of the material world, beginning with [[Saigyō]] at the end of the previous era, continued to be composed in the Kamakura period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} These works combined poetry describing the recluse life in thatched-hut retreats with magnificent essays called ''[[zuihitsu]]''{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} The most important examples are Kamo no Chōmei's ''[[Hōjōki]]'' and [[Kenkō]]'s ''[[Tsurezuregusa]]'' which was written around the very end of the Kamakura period and the beginning of the Nanbokuchō period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} The former describes its author's journey toward giving up the world, social changes, and celebrates recluse life, while the latter is a work of instruction detailing its author's inner thoughts and feelings as he lives in quiet seclusion.
{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}
Along with the classical ''[[Pillow Book]]'', they are considered the archetypal Japanese ''zuihitsu''{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

=== Buddhist literature and songs ===
The ''zuihitsu'' described above, written by monks training by living secluded lives in the wilderness, are of course a form of Buddhist literature, but it goes without saying that the most important specifically ''Buddhist'' literature consists of the writings of great monks of the various Japanese [[schools of Buddhism#Mahāyāna schools|Buddhist sects]] and the collections of their sayings that were produced by their followers.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} These include:
*[[Dōgen]]'s ''{{illm|Shōbō Genzō|ja|正法眼蔵}}'' and ''{{illm|Shōbō Genzō Zuimonki|ja|正法眼蔵随聞記}}'', the latter of which was recorded by his disciple<!-- "disciples"? -->;{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}
*''Mattōshō'' (末灯鈔), which collected the writings of [[Shinran]], and ''[[Tannishō]]'', a compilation of his teachings;{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}
*[[Nichiren]]'s ''{{illm|Kaimokushō|ja|開目抄}}'' and other works.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

Many of these Buddhist writings, or ''hōgo'', expound on deep philosophical principles, or explain the basics of Buddhism in a simple manner that could easily be digested by the uneducated masses.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

In addition to the continued production of ''{{illm|imayō|ja|今様}}'', ''[[sōka (song)|sōka]]'' (早歌) were created in large numbers, and their lyrics survive in textual form.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} Buddhist songs were performed as part of ''{{illm|ennen|ja|延年}}'', etc., and of particular note is the ''{{illm|wasan|ja|和讃}}'' form.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} Many of these ''wasan'' were supposedly created by Buddhist masters of the Heian period, but the form became prominent in the Kamakura period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} These songs were composed with the goal of educating people about Buddhism, and were widely recited around the country.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} Ichiko notes that the songs themselves are moving, but notes that Shinran's ''{{illm|Sanjō Wasan|ja|三帖和讃}}'' and later songs were particularly brilliant works of Buddhist literature.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

Furthermore, ''engi'' associated with famous temples, and illustrated biographies of Japanese Buddhist saints such as ''[[Kōya-daishi Gyōjō Zue]]'' (高野大師行状図絵), ''[[Hōnen-shōnin Eden]]'' (法然上人絵伝), ''[[Shinran-shōnin Eden]]'' (親鸞上人絵伝), ''{{illm|Ippen-shōnin Eden|ja|一遍聖絵}}'', continued to be produced during the Kamakura period and well into the Nanbokuchō period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} Ichiko notes that these should also be considered examples of the Buddhist literature of this period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

== Literature of the late medieval period ==
=== Historical background of the late medieval period ===
The late medieval period covers the roughly 270 years that, by conventional Japanese historiography, are classified as the Nanbokuchō (1333–1392), Muromachi (1392–1573) and Azuchi–Momoyama (1573–1600) periods.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} The conflict between the northern and southern courts in the Nanbokuchō period, and the frequent civil wars in the Muromachi period, caused massive social upheaval in this period, with the nobility (who were already in decline) losing virtually all of their former prestige, and lower classes moving upward to take their place.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} In particular, the high-level members of the warrior class took over from the aristocracy as the custodians of culture.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

The literature of this period was created by nobles, warriors, and hermits and artists of the lower classes.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} The popular literature and entertainment, which had previously been of little consequence, came into the limelight during this time.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} The ''[[Noh]]'' theatre came under the protection and sponsorship of the warrior class, with [[Kan'ami]] and his son [[Zeami]] bringing it to new artistic heights, while [[Nijō Yoshimoto]] and lower-class ''renga'' (linked verse) masters formalized and popularized that form.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

This is the point when "ancient" literature came to an end and was replaced with literature more representative of the early modern period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} This results in some degree of schizophrenia in the literature of this period, as contradictory elements are mixed freely.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} Deep and serious literature was combined with light and humorous elements, which is a noteworthy characteristic of late medieval literature.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} ''Noh'' and its comic counterpart ''[[kyōgen]]'' is the standard example of this phenomenon, but ''renga'' had ''[[haikai]]'', ''waka'' had its ''[[kyōka]]'' and ''[[kanshi (poetry)|kanshi]]'' (poetry in [[Classical Chinese]]) had its ''[[kyōshi]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} ''[[Monogatari-zōshi]]'' composed during this period combined the ''[[mono no aware|aware]]'' of the serious ''monogatari'' with characteristics of humorous anecdotes.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

Literature characterized by ''wabi-sabi'' was valued during this period of chaotic warfare.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} Commentary on and collation of the classics also came to the fore, with the "hidden traditions" of ''[[Kokinshū]]'' interpretation (''{{illm|kokin-denju|ja|古今伝授}}'') beginning.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} Furthermore, it was during this period that the classical Japanese literary tradition ceased to be the exclusive prerogative of the aristocracy, and passed into the hands of scholarly-minded warriors and hermits.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} [[Ichijō Kaneyoshi]] and {{illm|Sanjōnishi Sanetaka|ja|三条西実隆}} were noteworthy scholars of aristocratic origins, and in addition to writing commentaries such aristocratic scholars examined and compared a large volume of manuscripts.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} This opening up to the general populace of classical literature was also advanced by hermit ''renga'' masters such as [[Sōgi]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

Ichiko notes that while this reverence for the literature of the past was important, it is also a highly noteworthy characteristic of this period that new genres and forms, unlike those of earlier eras, prevailed.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} He also emphasizes that even though this was a period of bloody warfare and tragedy, the literature is often lively and bright, a trend that continued into the early modern period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}}

=== Literature in Chinese ===
Classical Chinese (''kanbun'') literature of the Heian period had been the domain of aristocratic men, but as the aristocracy fell from prominence writing in Chinese became more closely associated with [[Zen Buddhist]] monks.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=260}} Zen monks travelling back and forth between Japan and [[China]] brought with them the writings of [[Song dynasty|Song]] and [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]] China, and writing in Chinese by Japanese authors experienced something of a renaissance.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1pp=260–261}}

The Chinese literature produced during this period is known as the [[literature of the Five Mountains]] because of its close association with the monks of the [[Five Mountain System]].{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} The founder of the lineage was [[Yishan Yining]] (''Issan Ichinei'' in Japanese), an immigrant from Yuan China, and his disciples included [[Kokan Shiren]], [[Sesson Yūbai]], [[Musō Soseki]] and others, and these monks planted the seeds of the Five Mountains literary tradition.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Kokan's ''{{illm|Genkō Shakusho|ja|元亨釈書}}'' is an important work of this period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Ichiko remarks that while [[Chūgan Engetsu]] also created excellent writings at this time, it was Musō's disciples [[Gidō Shūshin]] and {{illm|Zekkai Chūshin|ja|絶海中津}} who brought the literature of the Five Mountains to its zenith.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

Musō and Gidō in particular had the ear of powerful members of the military class, to whom they acted as cultural and spiritual tutors.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} The tradition continued to flourish into the Muromachi period, when it came under the protection of the shogunate, but this led to its developing a tendency toward sycophancy, and while there continued to be exceptional individuals like [[Ikkyū Sōjun]], this period showed a general tendency toward stagnation and degradation.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Nevertheless, Ichiko notes, the literature of the Five Mountains had a profound impact on the cultural and artistic development of the Nanbokuchō period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

=== Late medieval ''waka'' ===
Four imperial anthologies were compiled during the Nanbokuchō period: three by the Nijō school and one, the ''[[Fūga Wakashū]]'', by the Kyōgoku school.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} The latter was directly compiled by [[Emperor Kōgon|retired emperor Kōgon]], and has the second gretest number of Kyōgoku poems after the ''Gyokuyō Wakashū''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} The ''[[Shin'yō Wakashū]]'', a quasi-''chokusenshū'' compiled by [[Prince Munenaga]], collects the works of the emperors and retainers of the Southern Court.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

In the Muromachi period, the ''waka'' composed by the nobility continued to stagnate, and after {{illm|Asukai Masayo|ja|飛鳥井雅世}} compiled the ''[[Shinshoku-kokin Wakashū]]'', the twenty-first imperial anthology, the age of court ''waka'' was at its end.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

The most important ''waka'' poets of this period were not courtiers but monks, hermits, and warriors. Examples of prominent monk-poets are the Nijō poet [[Ton'a]] in the Nanbokuchō period and [[Shōtetsu]] (who wrote the book of poetic theory ''{{illm|Shōtetsu Monogatari|ja|正徹物語}}'') and {{illm|Shinkei|ja|心敬}} (who was also a noted ''renga'' master) in the Muromachi period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Important ''waka'' poets of the samurai class include [[Imagawa Ryōshun]] in the early period, {{illm|Tō Tsuneyori|ja|東常縁}} (said to be the founder of the ''kokin-denju'' tradition) and others toward the middle of this period, and [[Hosokawa Yūsai]] at the very end of the middle ages.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Yūsai carried the ''waka'' tradition on into the early modern period, an act whose significance, Ichiko notes, should not be underestimated.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

=== ''Renga'' ===
Linked verse, or ''renga'', took the place of ''waka'' as the dominant poetic form during this period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} ''Renga'', or more specifically ''chō-renga'' (長連歌), emphasized wit and change, and was practiced in earlier times by both the nobility and commoners, but during the Nanbokuchō period Nijō Yoshimoto organized gatherings of both nobles and commoners and with the assistance of hermits like {{illm|Kyūsei|ja|救済 (連歌師)}} was able to formalize the ''renga'' tradition and compile the first true ''renga'' anthology, the ''[[Tsukuba-shū]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Yoshimoto also composed important books of ''renga'' theory such as ''[[Renri Hishō]]'' and ''[[Tsukuba Mondō]]'' (筑波問答).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

Later came notable poets like {{illm|Bontōan|ja|梵灯庵}}, but ''renga'' went into a brief period of stagnation until the [[Eikyō]] era (1429–1441), when the favour of the shōgun [[Ashikaga Yoshinori]] led to its being rejuvenated.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} The [[Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove (renga)|Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove]] (竹林の七賢), including such masters as {{illm|Sōzei|ja|宗砌}} and Shinkei were at their height during this period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Shinkei, who was also a prominent ''waka'' poet, wrote works of ''waka'' and ''renga'' theory such as ''[[Sasame-goto]]'' and ''[[Hitori-goto]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Sōgi, who was active from roughly the time of the Ōnin War, built on these developments and helped ''renga'' to reach its highest point.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} With {{illm|Kensai|ja|猪苗代兼載}} he compiled the ''[[Shinsen Tsukuba-shū]]'', and with his disciples {{illm|Shōhaku|ja|肖柏}} and {{illm|Sōchō|ja|宗長}} create ''renga'' masterpieces such as ''[[Minase Sangin Nannin Hyakuin]]'' (水無瀬三吟何人百韻) and ''[[Yuyama Sangin]]'' (湯山三吟).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

Sōgi's disciples Sōchō, [[Sōseki (renga poet)|Sōseki]] <small>([[:ja:宗碩|ja]])</small>, {{illm|Sōboku|ja|宗牧}} and other's carried on his legacy, teaching others and continuing the glory days of the genre.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} The most important ''renga'' master of the end of this period was {{illm|Satomura Jōha|ja|里村紹巴}}, who wrote ''[[Renga Shihō-shō]]'' (連歌至宝抄).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} He continued the practice of expanding ''renga'' to the masses, with his family (the [[Satomura clan]]) continuing to play a central role in the ''renga'' world into the Edo period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Under his influence, ''renga'' became fixed, causing it to stagnate, and leading to the increased popularity of ''[[haikai no renga]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

''Haikai'' had been popular even in the golden age of ''renga'', but went on the rise beginning with ''[[Chikuba Kyōgin-shū]]'' (竹馬狂吟集), the [[Ise Shrine|Ise]] priest [[Arakida Moritake]]'s ''[[Haikai no Renga Dokugin Senku]]'' (俳諧之連歌独吟千句, also known as ''Moritake Senku'' 守武千句) and [[Yamazaki Sōkan]]'s ''{{illm|Inu Tsukuba-shū|ja|新撰犬筑波集}}'' (''Haikai Renga-shō'' 俳諧連歌抄) in the late Muromachi period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} ''Haikai'' developed from ''renga'' at roughly the same time as ''kyōka'' developed from ''waka''.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Ichiko notes that while some ''haikai'' ventured too far into absurdity, they tapped into the popular spirit of the Japanese masses, and laid the groundwork for the major developments of the form in the early modern period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

=== ''Monogatari-zōshi'' ===
The ''giko-monogatari'' of the earlier period largely ceased during the Nanbokuchō period, and an incredibly large number of shorter works known as ''monogatari-zōshi'' (more commonly called ''[[otogi-zōshi]]'', a name that was applied later<!-- maybe?? -->) were created.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Many of them are unsophisticated and childish, and were written for a much broader audience than the earlier tale literature, which had been written by and for the aristocracy exclusively.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} As a result, they cover a much broader range of topics, and were written not only by nobles but by warriors, monks, hermits and urbanites.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

Of the works that continued the courtly tradition, some (such as ''[[Wakakusa Monogatari]]'') told romantic love stories and some (such as ''[[Iwaya no Sōshi]]'') contained stories of unfortunate<!-- ? --> stepchildren.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Among those about members of the warrior class, some (such as ''[[Shutendōji (otogi-zōshi)|Shutendōji]]'') drew upon ''gunki monogatari'' and heroic legends of monster-slayers, some (such as ''[[Onzōshi Shima-watari]]'') built legends of warriors, and others (such as ''[[Muramachi Monogatari]]'' and ''[[Akimichi]]'') told of chaos between rival houses and revenge.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} A very large number of them are about religious themes, reflecting the rise of popular Buddhism during this period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Some of these works (such as ''[[Aki no Yo no Naga Monogatari]]'') described monastic life, some (such as ''[[Sannin Hōshi]]'') expounded the virtues of seclusion, some (such as ''[[Kumano no Honji]]'') elaborate on the origins of temples and shrines in light of the concept of ''[[honji suijaku]]'', and some (such as ''[[Eshin-sōzu Monogatari]]'') are biographies of Buddhist saints.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}

In addition to the above works about nobles, warriors and monks, there are also a number of works in which the protagonists are farmers and urban commoners, known as ''risshin-shusse mono'' (立身出世物, "tales of rising up in the world") and ''shūgi-mono'' (祝儀物).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Examples of the former include ''[[Bunshō-zōshi]]'' (文正草子) and examples of the latter include ''[[Tsuru-Kame Monogatari]]'' (鶴亀物語).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} A number of these works are based on popular folk-tales, and reflect themes of ''[[gekokujō]]'' and the lively activity of the lower classes.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}} Several feature settings outside Japan, including the ''engi-mono'' of the early period and such works as ''[[Nijūshi-kō (otogi-zōshi)|Nijūshi-kō]] (二十四孝) and ''[[Hōman-chōja]]'' (宝満長者).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=261}}
